    <main class="content" role="main">

      <section id="why">
        <h2 class="section">Why this exists</h2>
        <p>
          Poke is a free software project with an open community. It was started by
          <a href="https://ashleyirispup.cat" target="_blank" rel="noopener">a queer, mixed-race trans girl with AUDHD</a> who wanted a YouTube frontend
          that doesn't spy on people. If that sentence already made you angry, this
          is a really good time to close the tab.
        </p>
        <p>
          Most people who show up here are great. Some aren't. This document exists
          so when someone comes in and starts being awful, there are clear rules
          and clear consequences already written down.
        </p>
        <p>
          This isn't about controlling what people think. But if you bring hate,
          harassment, or fascist garbage into this community, you're getting removed.
          Poke is a queer-friendly, anti-fascist project. That's not changing.
          If that upsets you, there are plenty of other places on the internet
          where you can go cry about it.
        </p>

        <details class="block">
          <summary>A note for right-wingers who want to make fun of this</summary>
          <p>
            Go for it. Seriously. Every time someone screenshots a code of conduct
            to post on X dot com with a crying-laughing emoji, it tells their
            followers exactly which communities won't tolerate them. That's free
            advertising for us.
          </p>
          <p>
            Here are some facts that tend to bother the people who get upset about
            documents like this:
          </p>
          <ul>
            <li>Trans people have existed in every culture throughout recorded history.
            The idea that this is "new" or a "trend" is historically illiterate.</li>
            <li>The overwhelming scientific and medical consensus supports gender-affirming care.
            Every major medical organization in the world agrees on this.</li>
            <li>Free software has always been political. Richard Stallman started the
            GNU Project in 1983 as an explicitly political act against proprietary
            software. If you think software shouldn't be political, you're about
            40 years too late.</li>
            <li>Diversity in tech teams consistently produces better software.
            This isn't an opinion, it's backed by research from MIT, Harvard,
            and dozens of other institutions.</li>
            <li>The countries with the strongest LGBTQ+ protections also consistently
            rank highest in press freedom, quality of life, and democratic governance.
            Funny how that works.</li>
          </ul>
          <p>
            Anyway, we're going to keep building free software and you're going to
            keep being mad about it. Have fun with that.
          </p>
        </details>
      </section>

      <section id="tldr">
        <h2 class="section">TL;DR</h2>
        <div class="callout">
          Be nice. Respect people's identities. Don't harass anyone. Don't post hate.
          Don't be a fascist. Don't spread misinformation. If you can manage that, welcome.
          If you can't, leave.
        </div>
        <p class="small" style="color:#999; margin-top:12px;">
          <strong style="color:#ccc;">a note on tone:</strong> this code of conduct has some humor in it.
          poke isn't a super serious corporate project and we don't write like one.
          the rules themselves are real and enforced, but the way we wrote them is
          casual on purpose because that's just how we talk. if some of it comes across
          as a bit cringe... yeah honestly fair lol. sorry about that. but we'd rather
          be a little cringe and clear than boring and unreadable. the actual rules still
          apply regardless of how many ":3" faces we put in the rest of the site.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section id="values">
        <h2 class="section">Our values</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Freedom</strong> - the <a href="https://www.gnu.org/philosophy/free-sw.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener">GNU kind</a>. the right to use, study, share, and modify software. also the freedom to exist as who you are.</li>
          <li><strong>Kindness</strong> - treat people like people. it costs nothing.</li>
          <li><strong>Inclusivity</strong> - this community is 2SLGBTQIA+-friendly, disability-friendly, neurodivergent-friendly, and furry-friendly by default. if that bothers you, this is not your project.

            <details class="block" style="margin-top:10px">
              <summary>What does 2SLGBTQIA+ mean?</summary>
              <p>
                <strong>2S</strong> - Two-Spirit. An umbrella term used by some Indigenous peoples to describe people who fulfill a traditional third-gender or other gender-variant role in their cultures. This is an Indigenous-specific identity and should not be used by non-Indigenous people to describe themselves.
              </p>
              <p>
                <strong>L</strong> - Lesbian. Women who are attracted to women.<br>
                <strong>G</strong> - Gay. People attracted to the same gender.<br>
                <strong>B</strong> - Bisexual. People attracted to more than one gender.<br>
                <strong>T</strong> - Transgender. People whose gender identity differs from the sex they were assigned at birth.<br>
                <strong>Q</strong> - Queer / Questioning. Queer is a broad umbrella term for anyone who isn't straight and/or isn't cisgender. Questioning means someone who is exploring their identity.<br>
                <strong>I</strong> - Intersex. People born with sex characteristics that don't fit typical definitions of male or female.<br>
                <strong>A</strong> - Asexual / Aromantic / Agender. Asexual people experience little or no sexual attraction. Aromantic people experience little or no romantic attraction. Agender people don't identify with any gender.<br>
                <strong>+</strong> - Everyone else. The community is bigger than any acronym. Pansexual, nonbinary, genderfluid, demisexual, and many more identities are all included.
              </p>
            </details>
          </li>
          <li><strong>Safety</strong> - people should be able to participate without worrying about being harassed, doxxed, or targeted.</li>
          <li><strong>Transparency</strong> - the code is free, the rules are public, enforcement is documented.</li>
          <li><strong>Honesty</strong> - we don't spread misinformation about software, people, or anything else. even if we don't like something, we tell the truth about it.</li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <section id="terminology">
        <h2 class="section">Terminology</h2>
        <p>
          A quick note on language we use in this project:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <strong>We say "free software," not "open source."</strong>
            This is a deliberate choice. The free software movement is about
            user freedom. "Open source" waters that down to a development
            methodology and strips out the ethical part. We care about the
            ethical part. For more on why this distinction matters, see
            <a href="https://www.gnu.org/philosophy/open-source-misses-the-point.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener">gnu.org/philosophy/open-source-misses-the-point</a>.
          </li>
          <li>
            When we refer to software licenses, we mean free software licenses
            as defined by the <a href="https://www.gnu.org/licenses/license-list.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Free Software Foundation</a>.
          </li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <section id="scope">
        <h2 class="section">Where this applies</h2>
        <p>
          This code of conduct applies everywhere Poke has a presence:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>The Codeberg repository (issues, pull requests, comments, wiki)</li>
          <li>Any official Poke chat rooms or community spaces</li>
          <li>Any other official Poke chat, forum, or social media account</li>
          <li>Pull requests, code, and documentation contributions</li>
          <li>Commit messages</li>
          <li>Official Poke instances and their public-facing content</li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          It also applies to behavior outside these spaces if that behavior targets
          Poke community members because of their participation in Poke.
          If you're harassing a contributor on their personal social media over
          something they did in this project, that counts.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section id="definitions">
        <h2 class="section">Definitions</h2>
        <p>
          So there's no room for "well technically" arguments:
        </p>

        <details class="block">
          <summary>Hate speech</summary>
          <p>
            Language, imagery, or behavior that attacks, dehumanizes, or calls for
            violence against people based on their race, ethnicity, nationality, caste,
            religion, gender, gender identity, sexual orientation, disability,
            neurodivergence, age, or species identity.
          </p>
          <p>
            This includes dogwhistles (yes, we know what those are) and "just joking"
            bigotry. If the punchline is that a group of people is lesser, it's hate speech.
          </p>
        </details>

        <details class="block">
          <summary>Slurs - the nuance</summary>
          <p>
            Using slurs <em>against</em> someone is always banned. Calling someone a
            slur to hurt them, dehumanize them, or put them down is hate speech,
            period.
          </p>
          <p>
            However, we recognize that <strong>reclaimed slurs</strong> are a real thing.
            If you're part of a group and you use a reclaimed term to refer to yourself
            or within your own community (like queer people using "queer," or Black
            people using the n-word among themselves), that's your right and we're not
            going to police that.
          </p>
          <p>
            The line is: are you using it about yourself / your own community in a
            way that community is okay with? Fine. Are you using it to attack someone
            or using a word that isn't yours to reclaim? Not fine. Moderators will
            use their judgment on context.
          </p>
        </details>

        <details class="block">
          <summary>Harassment</summary>
          <p>
            Any pattern of behavior directed at a specific person that makes them
            feel unsafe, unwelcome, or targeted. Including but not limited to:
          </p>
          <ul>
            <li>Repeated unwanted contact after being asked to stop</li>
            <li>Following someone across platforms to continue an argument</li>
            <li>Publishing or threatening to publish someone's private information (doxxing)</li>
            <li>Sexually explicit or romantic messages directed at someone who hasn't asked for them</li>
            <li>Deliberately and repeatedly misgendering someone</li>
            <li>Mocking someone's appearance, voice, typing style, or communication style</li>
            <li>Pile-ons: encouraging others to gang up on someone</li>
            <li>Screenshot-dunking: taking someone's messages out of context to mock them elsewhere</li>
          </ul>
          <p>
            A single message can be harassment if it's bad enough. You don't get
            a free first offense.
          </p>
        </details>

        <details class="block">
          <summary>Far-right / fascist content</summary>
          <p>
            Ideology, propaganda, or rhetoric that promotes or defends:
          </p>
          <ul>
            <li>White supremacy, white nationalism, or ethnonationalism of any kind</li>
            <li>Fascism, neo-nazism, or authoritarian ultranationalism</li>
            <li>Anti-2SLGBTQIA+ legislation, conversion therapy, or "gender critical" ideology</li>
            <li>Anti-immigrant movements or "great replacement" conspiracy theories</li>
            <li>MAGA, the American far-right movement, and its international equivalents</li>
            <li>Caste-based discrimination or advocacy for caste segregation</li>
            <li>Denial or trivialization of genocides, the Holocaust, slavery, or colonialism</li>
          </ul>
          <p>
            "I'm just asking questions" and "I'm just playing devil's advocate" don't
            get you a pass. If you're spreading fascist talking points, we don't care
            what rhetorical wrapper you put around them. Go complain about it on
            Truth Social or whatever, we genuinely do not care.
          </p>
        </details>

        <details class="block">
          <summary>Concern trolling</summary>
          <p>
            Pretending to be a well-meaning participant while actually trying to
            undermine the community, derail conversations, or normalize harmful ideas.
            Classic example: "I support trans people BUT..." followed by anti-trans rhetoric.
            Or asking moderators to "hear both sides" when one side is literal bigotry.
          </p>
        </details>

        <details class="block">
          <summary>Sealioning</summary>
          <p>
            Repeatedly demanding evidence, explanations, or debate from someone
            in bad faith. Usually looks like someone very politely but relentlessly
            asking a marginalized person to justify their own existence or prove
            that oppression is real. If you've been given an answer and you keep
            asking the same question in slightly different words, that's sealioning.
          </p>
        </details>

        <details class="block">
          <summary>Tone policing</summary>
          <p>
            Dismissing what someone is saying because of how they said it.
            If a trans person is angry about transphobia, telling them to
            "calm down" or "be more civil" instead of addressing the transphobia
            is tone policing. The person being harassed does not owe their
            harasser politeness.
          </p>
        </details>
      </section>

      <section id="prohibited">
        <h2 class="section">Prohibited conduct</h2>
        <p>
          The following will get you warned, temporarily banned, or permanently
          banned depending on severity. Moderators decide which. This list is
          organized by category so you can find what you're looking for, but
          all of it is equally enforceable.
        </p>

        <h3>Hate and bigotry</h3>
        <p class="small" style="color:#aaa;margin-top:4px;">
          Everyone is welcome in Poke regardless of who they are. Bigotry
          toward anyone is treated seriously here.
        </p>

        <div class="rule">
          <strong>Homophobia, biphobia, transphobia, enbyphobia, or queerphobia of any kind</strong>
          <span class="subtext">This includes "I don't hate them I just think..." type comments. You're not being subtle. We've heard it all before.</span>
        </div>

        <div class="rule">
          <strong>Racism, antisemitism, islamophobia, or xenophobia</strong>
          <span class="subtext">Includes "race realism," "western civilization" dogwhistles, triple parentheses, and all the other stuff people think is clever. It's not.</span>
        </div>

        <div class="rule">
          <strong>Caste-based discrimination or casteism</strong>
          <span class="subtext">Discrimination or harassment based on caste identity, advocacy for caste segregation, or dismissing caste oppression as "not real" or "just a cultural thing." Caste discrimination is a global human rights issue and it has no place here.</span>
        </div>

        <div class="rule">
          <strong>Ableism</strong>
          <span class="subtext">Mocking mental illness, neurodivergence, or disability. Using "autistic" or "r*tarded" as insults. Telling people to "just get over" their conditions. That kind of thing.</span>
        </div>

        <div class="rule">
          <strong>Misogyny, transmisogyny, or sexism</strong>
          <span class="subtext">Includes incel rhetoric and the whole "females" thing. To be clear: men do face real gender-based issues (custody bias, mental health stigma, workplace safety, etc.) and talking about those things is fine and welcome. What's not fine is using "men's rights" as a cover to attack women, feminists, or trans people. If you're advocating for men, great. If you're using it as a weapon against other people, that's misogyny with a rebrand. Also if you call women "females" unironically in 2026, we have questions about you.</span>
        </div>

        <div class="rule">
          <strong>Anti-furry, anti-otherkin, or anti-therian harassment</strong>
          <span class="subtext">These are real identities held by real people in this community. "Attack helicopter" jokes are from 2014 and they weren't funny then either.</span>
        </div>

        <div class="rule">
          <strong>Mocking anyone's religion, spiritual practices, or lack thereof</strong>
          <span class="subtext">You can criticize religious institutions and their political actions. You can't mock someone personally for what they believe or don't believe.</span>
        </div>

        <div class="rule">
          <strong>Colorism or texturism</strong>
          <span class="subtext">Discrimination based on skin tone within the same racial or ethnic group, or mocking hair texture. This is real and it happens. Don't do it here.</span>
        </div>

        <div class="rule">
          <strong>Fatphobia or body shaming</strong>
          <span class="subtext">Mocking someone's weight, body shape, or physical appearance. Concern trolling about someone's health as a way to bully them counts too.</span>
        </div>

        <h3>Harassment and abuse</h3>
        <p class="small" style="color:#aaa;margin-top:4px;">
          Harassment is any pattern of behavior that makes someone feel
          unsafe or unwelcome. Some of these are instant bans.
        </p>

        <div class="rule">
          <strong>Stalking, doxxing, or threatening anyone</strong>
          <span class="subtext">Publishing someone's real name, address, workplace, school, or any other private information. Threatening to do so counts too. Instant permanent ban.</span>
        </div>

        <div class="rule">
          <strong>Sexual harassment or unwanted sexual content</strong>
          <span class="subtext">Don't send people sexual messages they didn't ask for. NSFW content is only allowed in designated NSFW channels if the community space has them. Everywhere else, keep it clean. This should be obvious.</span>
        </div>

        <div class="rule">
          <strong>Deliberate misgendering or deadnaming</strong>
          <span class="subtext">If someone tells you their pronouns or their name, use them. "Accidentally" doing it over and over stops being an accident real fast.</span>
        </div>

        <div class="rule">
          <strong>Impersonating another person or community member</strong>
          <span class="subtext">Don't pretend to be someone you're not, whether that's another community member, a moderator, or a public figure.</span>
        </div>

        <div class="rule">
          <strong>Encouraging others to harass someone (brigading)</strong>
          <span class="subtext">Linking to someone's profile or messages with "look at this idiot" energy, rallying people to mass-report someone, etc.</span>
        </div>

        <div class="rule">
          <strong>Posting someone's private messages, real name, location, or photos without consent</strong>
          <span class="subtext">What happens in DMs stays in DMs unless there's a safety concern being reported to moderators.</span>
        </div>

        <div class="rule">
          <strong>Creating accounts to evade a ban</strong>
          <span class="subtext">If you got banned and you come back on an alt, that's another ban. We will keep doing this as long as you keep trying.</span>
        </div>

        <div class="rule">
          <strong>Grooming</strong>
          <span class="subtext">Building a relationship with someone (especially a minor) for the purpose of exploitation. This includes gradually normalizing sexual topics, isolating someone from other community members, giving someone special treatment to build dependency, or trying to move conversations to private unmoderated spaces. Applies to behavior toward anyone, not just minors, though grooming minors is treated with zero tolerance (see <a href="#minors">Protecting minors</a>).</span>
        </div>

        <div class="rule">
          <strong>CSAM, lolicon, shotacon, or any sexualized depiction of minors</strong>
          <span class="subtext">In any form. Drawings, AI-generated images, "fiction," fan art, whatever. There is no "but it's not real" defense. This is an instant permanent ban and a report to authorities. See <a href="#minors">Protecting minors</a> for the full policy.</span>
        </div>

        <div class="rule">
          <strong>Weaponizing reports</strong>
          <span class="subtext">Filing false or bad-faith reports to get someone in trouble, or mass-reporting someone you don't like. The report system is for safety, not revenge.</span>
        </div>

        <h3>Disruptive behavior</h3>
        <p class="small" style="color:#aaa;margin-top:4px;">
          Stuff that makes the community worse for everyone, even if
          it's not targeted at a specific person.
        </p>

        <div class="rule">
          <strong>Spamming channels, issues, or pull requests</strong>
          <span class="subtext">This includes AI-generated spam, repetitive messages, and low-effort mass-submissions.</span>
        </div>

        <div class="rule">
          <strong>Deliberately derailing conversations</strong>
          <span class="subtext">Turning every discussion into your personal soapbox, changing the subject to something inflammatory, etc.</span>
        </div>

        <div class="rule">
          <strong>Posting shock content, gore, or disturbing imagery</strong>
          <span class="subtext">There's no reason to post this stuff. Don't.</span>
        </div>

        <div class="rule">
          <strong>Using offensive or hateful usernames or profile pictures</strong>
          <span class="subtext">If your username is a slur or your pfp is a swastika, you're getting banned before you even say anything.</span>
        </div>

        <div class="rule">
          <strong>Concern trolling, sealioning, or tone policing</strong>
          <span class="subtext">See definitions above. We know what these look like. You're not as subtle as you think.</span>
        </div>

        <div class="rule">
          <strong>Main character syndrome</strong>
          <span class="subtext">Demanding constant attention, making every conversation about yourself, threatening to leave unless your demands are met. This is a community, not your personal support server.</span>
        </div>

        <h3>Political extremism</h3>
        <p class="small" style="color:#aaa;margin-top:4px;">
          Poke is explicitly anti-fascist. This isn't a centrist project
          pretending both sides are equal. Fascism is bad. That's our position.
        </p>

        <div class="rule">
          <strong>Promoting or defending fascism, nazism, or authoritarian regimes</strong>
          <span class="subtext">If you think fascism had "some good points" or that a dictator "wasn't that bad," you've already told us everything we need to know about you.</span>
        </div>

        <div class="rule">
          <strong>Posting far-right propaganda, memes, or recruitment material</strong>
          <span class="subtext">We know what the pipeline looks like. Pepe with the SS hat, "13/50" statistics, "despite making up..." copypastas. Save it for your echo chamber. Actually, don't save it at all. Go outside. Talk to a real person. Maybe read a book.</span>
        </div>

        <div class="rule">
          <strong>Defending or glorifying genocides, mass violence, or ethnic cleansing</strong>
          <span class="subtext">This includes Holocaust denial, slavery apologia, colonial nostalgia, and "but what about..." deflections. History happened. Deal with it.</span>
        </div>

        <div class="rule">
          <strong>Defending or glorifying billionaires who actively harm people</strong>
          <span class="subtext">Yes, including Elon Musk. The man bought a social media platform and turned it into a fascist recruitment tool. If that's your hero, you're in the wrong community.</span>
        </div>

        <div class="rule">
          <strong>Posting "ironic" hate imagery or dog whistles</strong>
          <span class="subtext">"It's just a joke" is not a defense. If your joke requires the audience to be bigoted to find it funny, it's not a joke, it's just bigotry with plausible deniability.</span>
        </div>

        <div class="rule">
          <strong>"Both sides" rhetoric about human rights</strong>
          <span class="subtext">There aren't two valid sides to "should trans people exist" or "was slavery bad." Some questions have answers. These questions have answers. If you want to debate whether marginalized people deserve rights, do it literally anywhere else.</span>
        </div>

        <div class="callout-red">
          If you think any of the above should be up for debate, this is not the community for you.
          You're free to go start your own project where you can be as hateful as you want.
          We hear Truth Social is nice this time of year. Well, actually, we hear it's terrible.
          But you'd fit right in.
        </div>
      </section>

      <section id="speech">
        <h2 class="section">Political speech</h2>
        <p>
          Poke is a political project whether people like that or not. Free software
          is political. Privacy is political. Running an alternative YouTube frontend
          that doesn't track people is political.
        </p>
        <p>
          We're not going to pretend to be neutral. Poke is pro-trans,
          pro-queer, pro-privacy, anti-fascist, and anti-corporate-surveillance.
          These are not debatable positions within this community. If you want a
          "both sides" debate about whether trans people deserve rights, go ask
          a right-wing subreddit. They love that stuff. We don't.
        </p>
        <p>
          You're welcome to have political opinions that differ from ours on things
          like economic policy, urban planning, or whatever. We're not a political
          party. But if your politics include "some people shouldn't have rights"
          then you're not welcome here.
        </p>

        <details class="block">
          <summary>What about "free speech"?</summary>
          <p>
            Free speech means the government can't arrest you for your opinions.
            It doesn't mean a free software project has to host your bigotry.
            We're not the government. We're a community with standards.
            You're free to say whatever you want somewhere else. Maybe on
            one of those "free speech" platforms that are somehow always full
            of nazis. Wonder why that is.
          </p>
        </details>
      </section>

      <section id="identity">
        <h2 class="section">Identity &amp; pronouns</h2>
        <p>
          Everyone in this community deserves to be referred to correctly.
          Not optional, not up for debate.
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Use the pronouns someone tells you to use.</strong> Every time. If you mess up, correct yourself and move on. Don't make it a big dramatic apology. Just fix it.</li>
          <li><strong>Neopronouns are valid.</strong> xe/xem, ze/zir, it/its, fae/faer, whatever someone uses. You don't need to understand something to respect it.</li>
          <li><strong>Some people use no pronouns.</strong> They want to be referred to by name only. That's valid. Use their name where you'd normally use a pronoun.</li>
          <li><strong>Deliberate misgendering is harassment.</strong> Doing it once and correcting yourself is a mistake. Doing it over and over is targeted harassment.</li>
          <li><strong>Deadnaming is harassment.</strong> If someone has a new name, use it. Their old name is not your business.</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Non-human identities</h3>
        <p>
          This community welcomes otherkin, therians, furries, robotkin, plural
          systems, and anyone else. These are real identities held by real people
          and they get the same respect as any other identity here.
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>Mocking someone for being otherkin, therian, or furry is harassment</li>
          <li>"Identifying as an attack helicopter" type jokes are stale and unfunny and will get you banned</li>
          <li>Plural systems (people with multiple identities sharing one body) are welcome and their system members are treated as individuals</li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <section id="minors">
        <h2 class="section">Protecting minors &amp; CSAM policy</h2>
        <p>
          People under 18 participate in free software communities and they
          participate in ours. They're welcome here and protecting them is
          everyone's responsibility.
        </p>

        <div class="callout-red">
          <strong>CSAM (child sexual abuse material), lolicon, shotacon, or any
          sexualized depiction of minors in any form is permanently banned.</strong>
          This includes drawings, AI-generated content, "fiction," fan art, and
          anything else. There is no "but it's not real" exception. There is no
          "it's just art" exception. If it sexualizes minors in any way, it
          results in an immediate permanent ban and a report to the relevant
          authorities. Zero tolerance. Zero exceptions. Zero appeals.
        </div>

        <h3>Rules</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>Do not post sexual or NSFW content anywhere in Poke spaces except designated NSFW channels (if present). Even in NSFW channels, all content must involve adults only.</li>
          <li>Do not send sexual messages to anyone who hasn't consented to receiving them, and <strong>never</strong> to minors under any circumstances.</li>
          <li>Do not ask minors for personal information, photos, location, age verification selfies, or anything else that a reasonable person would find creepy.</li>
          <li>Do not engage in grooming behavior. This means: building a relationship with a minor for the purpose of sexual exploitation, gradually normalizing sexual topics with a minor, isolating a minor from other community members, or giving a minor special attention/gifts/roles to build trust for exploitation.</li>
          <li>Do not send minors private messages with sexual, romantic, or otherwise inappropriate content.</li>
          <li>Do not try to move conversations with minors to private platforms, encrypted chats, or off-community spaces in a way that isolates them from moderation.</li>
          <li>Adults who engage in any predatory behavior toward minors will be permanently banned and reported to relevant authorities. No warning, no second chance, no appeal.</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>What grooming looks like</h3>
        <p>
          Grooming isn't always obvious. It can look like an older community member
          being "really nice" to a younger one, giving them special attention,
          slowly introducing sexual topics into conversation, or trying to get them
          to communicate on private platforms away from moderators. If you see
          something that feels off, report it. We would rather investigate
          something and find out it's fine than miss something that wasn't.
        </p>

        <p>
          If you are a minor and an adult in this community is making you
          uncomfortable in any way, please tell a moderator. You will be believed
          and the situation will be handled.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section id="misinfo">
        <h2 class="section">Misinformation</h2>
        <p>
          We care about honesty. Spreading false information in Poke spaces is
          not allowed, even when it's about stuff we don't like.
        </p>

        <div class="rule">
          <strong>Don't spread blatant misinformation about software</strong>
          <span class="subtext">
            Even about proprietary software. You can criticize Windows, macOS,
            Chrome, or any other proprietary software all you want, and we
            encourage that. But stick to the real problems (and there are plenty).
            Don't make stuff up. Don't say "Windows sends all your files to
            the NSA" if you can't back that up. Don't use silly names like
            "Microslop" or "Winblows" and then present made-up claims as fact.
            The real issues with proprietary software are bad enough without
            inventing fake ones.
          </span>
        </div>

        <div class="rule">
          <strong>Don't spread misinformation about people</strong>
          <span class="subtext">
            Don't make up stuff about community members, maintainers, or anyone
            else. Don't fabricate screenshots. Don't put words in people's mouths.
          </span>
        </div>

        <div class="rule">
          <strong>Don't spread conspiracy theories as fact</strong>
          <span class="subtext">
            Flat earth, anti-vax, QAnon, "5G causes cancer," any of that.
            You can discuss these topics critically (like debunking them),
            but presenting conspiracy theories as truth will get you warned
            or removed.
          </span>
        </div>

        <div class="rule">
          <strong>Don't present pseudoscience as fact in technical discussions</strong>
          <span class="subtext">
            This includes things like young earth creationism (the claim that
            the Earth is 6,000-10,000 years old), flat earth theory, or
            anti-evolution claims being presented as science. To be very clear:
            we respect people's religious faith. Christianity, Islam, Judaism,
            Hinduism, and every other religion are welcome here, and personal
            spiritual beliefs are not something we police. Many deeply faithful
            people also accept the scientific evidence for an old Earth and
            evolution, and that's between them and their faith. But Poke is a
            software project that relies on science and engineering, and in
            technical contexts, established science is what we go by. You're
            free to believe whatever you want personally. Just don't derail
            technical discussions with claims that contradict well-established
            scientific consensus.
          </span>
        </div>

        <p>
          The short version: criticize things for real reasons with real evidence.
          The free software movement has plenty of legitimate criticisms of
          proprietary software, surveillance capitalism, and corporate control.
          You don't need to make stuff up, and doing so actually hurts the
          credibility of the real arguments.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section id="contributions">
        <h2 class="section">Code &amp; contributions</h2>
        <p>
          When you contribute code, documentation, or other work to Poke:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Write descriptive commit messages.</strong> "fixed the thing" is bad. "fix video playback crash on iOS Safari when seeking" is good.</li>
          <li><strong>No hateful content in code.</strong> Variable names, comments, strings, Easter eggs, test data. If a moderator finds slurs in your test fixtures, that's a ban.</li>
          <li><strong>Don't submit malicious code.</strong> Backdoors, data exfiltration, intentional vulnerabilities, or code designed to harm users will get you permanently banned and may be reported.</li>
          <li><strong>Don't submit code you don't have the right to submit.</strong> If it's from a project with an incompatible license, don't put it in Poke. We take <a href="https://www.gnu.org/licenses/gpl-3.0.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener">free software licensing</a> seriously.</li>
          <li><strong>Don't spam pull requests.</strong> Low-effort PRs that change whitespace, rename variables for no reason, or "fix typos" that aren't actually typos are disruptive and annoying.</li>
          <li><strong>Review comments should be constructive.</strong> "This code sucks" is not a review. "This could cause a memory leak because X, here's a suggestion" is a review.</li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <section id="ai">
        <h2 class="section">AI content policy</h2>
        <p>
          When we say "AI" in this section, we mean <strong>generative AI</strong>:
          large language models (LLMs), image generators, voice synthesizers, and
          similar tools that create text, images, audio, or code from prompts.
          We don't mean video game AI, spam filters, autocomplete, or any of
          the other things that have been called "AI" for decades. Those are fine.
          This section is specifically about generative AI tools.
        </p>

        <p>
          Using generative AI tools is allowed in Poke as long as you're honest
          about it and you're not causing problems. We don't endorse any specific
          AI provider since no LLM company is without issues, but we're not going
          to ban people from using tools that exist. Just be upfront about it.
        </p>

        <ul>
          <li><strong>Label AI-generated content.</strong> If you used a generative AI to write code, generate text, or create an image, say so. Don't pass it off as your own work.</li>
          <li><strong>Don't flood with AI content.</strong> Submitting dozens of AI-generated issues, PRs, or messages is spam regardless of quality.</li>
          <li><strong>Don't use AI to generate hate material, fake screenshots, impersonations, or propaganda.</strong></li>
          <li><strong>Don't use AI to create fake community members or fake consensus.</strong> If you're using a chatbot to pretend to be multiple people agreeing with you, that's ban-worthy and also genuinely pathetic.</li>
          <li><strong>AI-generated code in PRs must be reviewed and understood by the person submitting it.</strong> If you can't explain what your PR does because a chatbot wrote it, don't submit it.</li>
          <li><strong>Using AI to help with translation, documentation, debugging, or brainstorming is fine</strong> as long as you review the output, it's accurate, and you're transparent about it.</li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <section id="disagreements">
        <h2 class="section">Disagreements &amp; conflict</h2>
        <p>
          People disagree. That's normal. Technical disagreements, different
          priorities, different opinions on implementation, that's all part of
          working on software together.
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Argue about the idea, not the person.</strong> "I think this approach has a problem because X" is fine. "You clearly don't know what you're doing" is not.</li>
          <li><strong>Know when to stop.</strong> If a discussion is going in circles, step away. Come back later or let a maintainer make the call.</li>
          <li><strong>Maintainers have final say on technical decisions.</strong> You can disagree, but once a decision is made, accept it or fork the project. That's how free software works.</li>
          <li><strong>Don't take technical disagreements personal.</strong> Someone rejecting your PR is not a personal insult.</li>
          <li><strong>If you're getting heated, take a break.</strong> Close the tab. Go do something else. Come back when you're calm.</li>
        </ul>

        <div class="callout-warn">
          If a disagreement turns into personal attacks or harassment,
          moderators will step in. You may not like the outcome.
        </div>
      </section>

      <section id="enforcement">
        <h2 class="section">Enforcement</h2>
        <p>
          Moderators and maintainers enforce these rules. They have discretion
          to act on anything that harms the community, even if it's not
          explicitly listed here. If you're being awful in a way we didn't
          think to write down, you can still be removed.
        </p>

        <h3>Levels</h3>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Verbal warning.</strong> A moderator tells you to stop. This is a courtesy. Take it seriously.</li>
          <li><strong>Message removal.</strong> Your message gets deleted. If it keeps happening, a ban follows.</li>
          <li><strong>Temporary ban.</strong> You're locked out for a set period. How long depends on what you did.</li>
          <li><strong>Permanent ban.</strong> You're removed forever. This is for hate speech, harassment, predatory behavior, or repeated violations.</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>What doesn't get a warning first</h3>
        <p>
          Some things skip straight to a ban:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>CSAM, lolicon, shotacon, or any sexualized depiction of minors</li>
          <li>Grooming or predatory behavior toward minors</li>
          <li>Slurs or hate speech directed at someone</li>
          <li>Doxxing or threats of violence</li>
          <li>Posting nazi/fascist imagery or propaganda</li>
          <li>Ban evasion</li>
          <li>Submitting malicious code</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Appeals</h3>
        <p>
          If you were temporarily banned and you think it was a mistake, you
          can email <span class="mono">iamashley@duck.com</span> with your
          side of the story. Be honest, be specific. Appeals for permanent
          bans due to hate speech or predatory behavior will not be considered.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section id="reporting">
        <h2 class="section">Reporting</h2>
        <p>
          If someone is violating this code of conduct, please report it:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>Email: <span class="mono">iamashley@duck.com</span></li>
          <li>Community chat: DM a moderator in any official Poke chat space</li>
          <li>Codeberg: <a href="https://codeberg.org/ashleyirispuppy/poke/issues" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Open an issue</a> (for non-sensitive stuff)</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>What happens when you report</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>Your report is seen by the moderation team, not the whole community</li>
          <li>We'll look at what happened and take action if the rules were broken</li>
          <li>We won't reveal who reported unless you specifically say it's okay</li>
          <li>Retaliating against someone for making a report is itself a bannable offense</li>
        </ul>

        <p>
          If you're not sure whether something crosses the line, report it
          anyway. We'd rather look at something and decide it's fine than
          miss something that needed action.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section id="naming">
        <h2 class="section">Naming &amp; modification rules</h2>
        <p>
          This code of conduct is licensed under CC BY-SA 4.0, so you can share
          and remix it. But if you modify it, you can't use names that imply
          it's the official Poke version. Modified versions cannot be called:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>Poke Code of Conduct</li>
          <li>Poketube Code of Conduct</li>
          <li>Poke Project Code of Conduct</li>
          <li>Poke Community Guidelines</li>
          <li>Or any other name that implies official Poke endorsement</li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          If you change it, rename it clearly. If someone forks this and
          rewrites it to allow hate or remove protections for marginalized
          people, we reserve the right to publicly call that out.
        </p>

        <details class="block">
          <summary>Legal text</summary>
          <p>
            By using or redistributing this work (or any derivative), you agree
            to these naming and modification rules. If you distribute a modified
            version, you <strong>must</strong> change its name/title so as not to
            imply it is the official "Poke Code of Conduct." You <strong>may not</strong>
            call your modified document "Poke," "Poketube," or any variant thereof
            unless the version is entirely unchanged. This name-change requirement
            binds all downstream recipients of derivative versions.
          </p>
        </details>
      </section>

      <section id="contact">
        <h2 class="section">Contact</h2>
        <p>
          Questions, concerns, or reports:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>Email: <span class="mono">iamashley@duck.com</span></li>
          <li>Community chat: DM a moderator in any official Poke chat space</li>
          <li>Codeberg: <a href="https://codeberg.org/ashleyirispuppy/poke/issues" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Open an Issue</a></li>
